Why you need it?

- to make sure your AsyncAPI spec file follows INGKA API standards;
- to automate AsyncAPI linting as part of your CI/CD pipeline;

How to add and configure existing rules?

You can use any rule which comes out of the box of `spectral` package. Full list of those rules may be found here. In order to override the severity of the rule which is being added via the `recommended` config, simply add it to the asyncapiRulset.ts under the `rules` property like this:

```typescript
// src/asyncapiRulset.ts

export default {
  ...
  rules: {
    // Overriding severity of the rule from the recommended config
    'asyncapi-info-description': 'error',
  }
}
```

How to create custom rules?

In order to create custom rules you can:

- create custom rule with spectral built-in assertion functions;
- create custom assertion functions (if built-in functions do not fulfill the required functionality);

Below you may find an example of a custom rule, which uses both spectral built-in functions and custom functions:

```typescript
// src/asyncapiRuleset.ts

import { defined } from '@stoplight/spectral-functions';

export default {
  ...
  rules: {
    // The rule ID should be unique, meaningful and start with a `custom-` prefix.
    'custom-info-version': {
      // `message` is the problem message that will be shown in case the assertion is false.
      message: 'Version must be present and follow semantic versioning.',
      // `severity` helps to define the importance of following the rule.
      severity: 'error',
      // `given` tells Spectral which part of the JSON or YAML file to target by using JSONPath (Spectral uses JSONPath Plus).
      given: '$.info',
      // `then` specifies which properties of the `given` object should be validated and which assertion to use.

then: [
        {
          // `field` is the property within the path (defined by property `given`) which custom rule should assert.
          field: 'version',
          // `function` contains an assertion which will be used against the `field`.
          // Spectral has a set of built-in assertion functions such as `truthy` or `pattern`,
          // which can be used when validating the `field`.
          // Here we are using a built-in `defined` assertion.
          // These functions can be imported from the `@stoplight/spectral-functions` package.
          function: defined,
        },
      ],
    },
  }
}
```

Custom assertion functions can be passed in `function` property same as spectral built-in functions. An example of a custom function implementation is shown below:

```typescript
// src/functions/fieldLength.ts

export function fieldLength(input: string, options: { min: number }): object[] {
  // Condition is handled in spectral standard rules so it's better to leave it.
  if (!input) {
    return [];
  }

  if (input.length < options.min) {
    // Return a problem because assertion is false.

return [
      {
        message: `Write a well formatted brief description of your API with at least 30 char long.`,
      },
    ];
  }

  return [];
}
```

Why you need it?

- to make sure your OpenAPI spec file follows INGKA API standards;
- to automate OpenAPI linting as part of your CI/CD pipeline;

As an NPM package

> **_Recommendation:_** use **as a CLI** and pass the path to the OpenAPI specification .yaml file

```sh
lint-openapi ./examples/openapi-01.yaml
```

OR

> **_Recommendation:_** use **as a JS module** in your own application

```ts
// example.ts
import { lintFromFilePaths, lintFromString } from '@ingka-group-digital/lint-openapi';

// 1. In order to print out the linting result:
await lintFromFilePaths(['./examples/openapi-01.yaml']);

// 2. In order to return an output object:
const stringifiedOpenApiSpec = 'stringified-openapi-spec';
const linterOutput = await lintFromString(stringifiedOpenApiSpec);
```

Adding a registry entry to .npmrc

Open up your project's `.npmrc` and add these two lines:

```
@ingka-group-digital:registry=https://artifactory.build.ingka.ikea.com/artifactory/api/npm/ingka-npm-shared-local/
//artifactory.build.ingka.ikea.com/artifactory/api/npm/ingka-npm-shared-local/:_auth=${ARTIFACTORY_AUTH_TOKEN}
```

The next section will explain how to get and set the `ARTIFACTORY_AUTH_TOKEN`.

How to create custom rules?

In order to create custom rules you can:

- use out-of-the-box assertions;
- create custom assertion functions;

Below you may find an example of a custom rule, which uses both out-of-the-box assertions and custom ones:

```yaml

keywords:
          - foo
          - bar
```

Custom assertion functions, one of which (`checkIfContainsKeywords`) we referenced in the example above, are declared in the custom-rules-plugin.js file:

```js
// custom-rules-plugin.js

module.exports = {
  id: 'custom',
  assertions: {
    checkIfContainsKeywords: (description, options, location) => {
      const hasOneOfKeywords = options.keywords.some(keyword => description.includes(keyword));

      // Return no problem because assertion is true.
      if (hasOneOfKeywords) {
        return [];
      }

      // Return a problem because assertion is false.
      return [{ message: `Description doesn't contain any of the keywords.`, location }];
    },
  },
};
```

For more information about `redocly` rules, custom rules and related data objects, read more information on this page.

For more information about OpenAPI model and node types, which could be used in creation of the custom rules, read more information on this page.
